 Governor Godwin Obaseki of Edo State, on Wednesday, sent five bills to the Edo State House of Assembly, including the Disability Rights Bill which seeks to end all forms of discrimination against persons with disabilities. Obaseki also sent the Electricity Commission and Agency Bill that aims to increase access to electricity to Edo State residents. The Edo State Commissioner for Communication and Orientation, Andrew Emwanta, gave the hint during a press briefing held after the weekly Edo State Executive Council meeting presided over by the governor at the Government House in Benin City. Also sent were the Edo Property Development Agency Bill, the Criminal Law Bill of Edo State, and the Justice Reform Bill. Emwanta said that the bills were discussed extensively with corrections effected. He stated that clean copies of the bills would be sent to the Edo State House of Assembly. The Commissioner for Education, Dr. Joan Osa-Oviawe, stated that external candidates would no longer be allowed to write exams in schools across the state. She said that “The EXCO mandated the Ministry of Education to put out a public announcement to inform parents and proprietors of private schools as well as public schools’ principals that effective immediately, no external candidates will be allowed to write any exams in Edo. “This affects West African Examinations Council and National Examination Council, Junior Secondary School, as well as primary six exams. The EXCO is only reinforcing this message for the ministry implementation extant policy; this is not a new thing.” 